images.name: Stanford rallies to advance to Sweet 16
images.caption: Stanford rallies from a four-point deficit at the beginning to the fourth quarter to defeat South Dakota State 66-65.

article.linkText: Stanford survives on 3-point play with 8.2 to go
article.story:
STANFORD, Calif. -- Lili Thompson had to forget her miss that could have cost Stanford its season. There was still time left.

"You kind of hear it growing up: You have to have a short memory," Thompson said.

She delivered when it mattered most. Thompson converted a go-ahead 3-point play with 8.2 seconds left, and Erica McCall delivered a big block moments later to lift No. 4 seed Stanford into the Sweet 16 with a 66-65 comeback win over 12th-seeded South Dakota State on Monday.

Stanford needed every last tick of the clock to extend its long run of regional semifinals appearances to nine.

McCall swatted Macy Miller's shot in the key with one second left to seal the win. Thompson, who missed a 3-point try with 18 seconds to go, made a driving layup with 8.2 seconds left and converted the free throw as the Cardinal erased a five-point deficit over the final three minutes.

"She is the one. You want the ball in her hands," McCall said of Thompson. "She is clutch. This girl is crazy good."

What a finish for Tara VanDerveer's team in the Hall of Fame coach's 1,000th game at Stanford. The Cardinal (26-7) will face Notre Dame on Friday in the Lexington Regional.

VanDerveer hated to see South Dakota State's special season end, considering how hard and with how much passion the opponent played.

"Tonight we played against a team that executed really well, a team that was extremely well-coached and a team that put their heart on the floor," VanDerveer said. "Honestly, I wish they'd been in a different bracket because it was sad to see them lose when they had played so well."

South Dakota State (27-7) missed a chance to reach the Sweet 16 for the first time in program history, despite pushing the Cardinal to the end at Maples Pavilion, where they have been so dominant in the NCAAs.

"We wanted to be that first team that made it to the Sweet 16," guard Kerri Young said. "We got a pretty good lead, they went on a little bit of a run, and we kind of fell and didn't really counter that and make runs back at them. That's what changed the game."

Briana Roberson hit a 3-pointer with 1:11 left to pull Stanford within 64-63. Immediately after Thompson's missed 3 at 18 seconds, Miller couldn't convert the second of two free throws. VanDerveer called timeout before Thompson's winning play.

"Every person, every basket, every rebound was one of those coaches like to talk about because each play mattered," VanDerveer said.

Stanford survived for its 14th straight NCAA win at home. The most recent loss came when Florida State stunned the Cardinal 68-61 on March 19, 2007 in the second round at Maples.

The Cardinal overcame shooting 10 for 22 from the free throw line -- "horrendous," VanDerveer said -- while the Jackrabbits were 7-for-13 after struggling Saturday in their first-round upset of fifth-seeded Miami.

Miller converted a 3-point play with 6:01 left to put South Dakota State ahead 58-51, then Ellie Thompson hit from long range at 4:41 for a 62-54 lead that forced Stanford to use a timeout.

McCall scored 13 of her 20 points in the first half but was largely held in check the rest of the way. Thompson wound up with 19 points and five assists.

Gabby Boever was held to three points on 1-of-7 shooting in her final collegiate game, while Thompson had 14 points and Young 13.

HEARTBREAKING FINISH

South Dakota State's loyal, blue-clad, traveling fan base is headed home from rainy Northern California to snow in the forecast.

In 2009, the Jackrabbits reached the second round for the first time after five first-round exits.

"You knew it was going to come down to the end," coach Aaron Johnston said. "It'll probably be quite a while before I go back and watch this."

TIP-INS

South Dakota State: After struggling to take care of the ball late in a first-round win over No. 5 seed Miami, the Jackrabbits didn't turn the ball over once in the opening quarter and finished with seven turnovers. ... The Jackrabbits have never reached a regional. ... They had won five straight games and 18 of 21. ... There will be more NCAA women's basketball in basketball-crazed South Dakota, with Sioux Falls hosting a regional this weekend.

Stanford: VanDerveer, who coached her 1,203rd career game, is 21 victories from joining Pat Summitt as the only NCAA women's coaches with 1,000 career wins. ... The Cardinal improved to 34-4 in NCAA games on their home floor. ... The 65 NCAA women's games played at Maples are second-most at any venue, behind Tennessee's Thompson-Boling Arena (66).

UP NEXT

South Dakota State's season is over.

Stanford faces Notre Dame on Friday.
